## Historical Background  
### Early days of machine learning automation  
The notion of automating the grunt work of **machine learning** isn’t brand new; it has roots that stretch back to the era when **Data preprocessing** ([Data_preprocessing](/Data_preprocessing)) was done on punch cards and the only “hyperparameter” you could tweak was the size of your batch. Early **Statistical learning** methods like **Support vector machines** ([Support vector machine](/Support_vector_machine)) had manual tuning parameters that required a PhD and a caffeine addiction to adjust.  

### The rise of neural architecture search  
Fast forward to the deep‑learning boom, and suddenly everyone wanted to build **Neural networks** ([Neural_network](/Neural_network)) that could outperform humans on everything from image classification to generating poetry about existential dread. Enter **Neural architecture search** ([Neural_architecture_search](/Neural_architecture_search)), a set of algorithms that literally *search* for the best architecture configuration. Google’s **AutoML** ([AutoML](/AutoML)) suite, launched in 2018, was the first high‑profile system to let users outsource the architecture design to a meta‑learning loop that treated each candidate model like a contestant on a reality TV show – eliminated if it didn’t improve validation accuracy.  

