## Key Features and Techniques  
### Hyperparameter optimization  
AutoML treats **Hyperparameter optimization** ([Hyperparameter_optimization](/Hyperparameter_optimization))) as a core sub‑problem, often employing Bayesian optimization, genetic algorithms, or – because we’re feeling dramatic – random search that pretends to be systematic. The process typically involves defining a search space (e.g., learning‑rate ∈ [0.001, 0.1]), then letting the algorithm explore it while judging each configuration against a validation set. The result is a model that, in theory, has hyperparameters tuned to a level that would make a seasoned **Deep learning** ([Deep_learning](/Deep_learning))) practitioner weep with envy.  

### Neural architecture search  
If you thought **Neural architecture search** was just a fancy term for “trying different layer counts,” think again. Modern NAS methods can design entire **Convolutional neural network** ([Convolutional_neural_network](/Convolutional_neural_network))) backbones, decide on skip connections, and even pick activation functions on the fly. Some approaches, like reinforcement‑based NAS, treat the search process as a **Reinforcement learning** ([Reinforcement_learning](/Reinforcement_learning))) problem where a controller agent receives rewards for discovering architectures that achieve higher test scores. The output is a model that, if you stare at its diagram long enough, starts to look like a modern art piece titled *“My Mom’s First CNN.”*  

### Feature engineering automation  
AutoML doesn’t just stop at model selection; it also tries to **automate feature engineering** ([Feature_engineering](/Feature_engineering)) – the art of turning raw data into something a model can actually digest. Techniques include **One‑hot encoding** ([One_hot_encoding](/One_hot_encoding)) of categorical variables, **Imputation** of missing values, and even **Temporal feature creation** for time‑series data. Some frameworks generate dozens of candidate features automatically, then let a downstream algorithm rank them by importance, effectively turning the user into a passive observer of a feature‑generation circus.  

### Model selection and ensemble methods  
When the search space is too large for a single model to explore, AutoML often resorts to **Ensemble methods** ([Ensemble_learning](/Ensemble_learning))) like stacking or voting, combining the predictions of multiple candidates to improve robustness. It may also select the “best” model based on a metric such as **Area under the ROC curve** ([AUC](/AUC))) for classification or **Root mean square error** ([RMSE](/Root_mean_square_error))) for regression. The selection process is usually accompanied by a terse comment like “I’ve seen better models on my lunch break,” which, in true Emma fashion, is both accurate and mildly insulting.  

### Pipeline orchestration  
All of the above steps are typically wrapped in a **pipeline** that can be executed end‑to‑end with a single command. This pipeline may be expressed in a declarative language (e.g., **YAML** or **JSON**) or as a visual drag‑and‑drop interface. The key selling point is **reproducibility**: run the same pipeline on the same dataset, and you should get (almost) identical results, barring stochastic variations that the system will blame on “the whims of the universe.”  

