## Controversies or Criticisms  
### Overhyped promises  
Critics argue that AutoML is often marketed with a level of hyperbole that would make a 19th‑century snake‑oil salesman blush. Phrases like “state‑of‑the‑art performance with zero expertise required” are tossed around, ignoring the fact that **data quality** ([Data_quality](/Data_quality))) still matters more than any fancy algorithm. In practice, many AutoML platforms struggle with high‑dimensional data, rare classes, or domain‑specific constraints that require human intuition to resolve.  

### Black‑box opacity  
Another major criticism is the **black‑box opacity** inherent in many AutoML pipelines. When a model is selected automatically, the resulting architecture may be a sprawling network of layers whose purpose is opaque even to its creators. This makes debugging a nightmare: you can’t just “look at the weights” and say “ah, that’s why it’s failing.” Instead, you’re forced to rely on post‑hoc explanation tools that themselves are imperfect, leading to a chain of models trying to explain other models – a meta‑black‑box.  

### Reproducibility issues  
Reproducibility is a cornerstone of scientific research, yet many AutoML frameworks introduce stochastic elements (e.g., random search, nondeterministic GPU kernels) that can cause results to vary wildly across runs. This undermines claims of “deterministic pipelines” and forces users to set arbitrary seeds or accept that “the model chose a different architecture today because it felt like it.”  

